        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>lip-vibrated aerophones with conical bore: natural [300224126], lip-vibrated aerophones with conical bore [300195078], lip-vibrated aerophones [300041639], aerophones [300041622], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Long straight trumpetlike aerophones of slightly conical bore, made of brass or silver with several joints, their junctions concealed by ornamental bosses, and a flared bell. They were used as heralds' trumpets in Medieval Europe and often bore the standard of a noble person.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Instrumentos de viento largos y rectos similares a trompas, de diámetro interior ligeramente cónico, hechos de bronce o plata con varios ensambles, cuyos empalmes se disimulaban mediante relieves ornamentales, y una campana ensanchada. Se usaron en la Europa medieval como trompetas de los heraldos y a menudo llevaban el distintivo de un noble.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Lange rechte trompetachtige aërofonen met een licht conische boring gemaakt van messing of zilver en waarvan de verbindingsstukken worden verborgen met ornamentele uitstulpingen en met een wijd uitlopende klankbeker. Ze werden in de Middeleeuwen in Europa gebruikt als herautentrompetten en droegen vaak het wapen van een edelman.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>既長又直、狀似喇叭/小號的管樂器，其口徑略呈圓錐形，是由黃銅或者是銀所製作而成的，有數個連接處，它們的連接點是由裝飾性的浮雕所遮蓋，並且有著一個喇叭形狀的喇叭口。它們在中古世紀的歐洲是用來做為(舊時君主的)傳令官、報信者/使者的喇叭/小號，並且經常具備著一位貴族的標準。 </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Langes und gerades, trompetenähnliches Aerofon mit leicht konischer Röhre, aus Messing oder Silber gefertigt, mit mehreren Verbindungsstücken, deren Übergänge mit verzierten Bossen kaschiert waren, und mit einem ausgestellten Schalltrichter. Die Busine wurde als Heroldstrompete im Europa des Mittelalters benutzt und trug oft die Standarte eines Adligen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
